{"author":"Joe Oakhart","author_email":"joeoakhart+bot@navapbc.com","author_id":"594c-9dcf-5ad6-4e6d","data":{"fields":{"description":"# Build-once artifact identity + fix the provenance hook's None-commit path\n\nRestructure the release graph so the exact wheel and sdist are built once, tested\nin a clean environment, and published byte-for-byte, and fix the Hatchling hook so\nthe wheel-from-sdist path never bakes `COMMIT = None`. (Readiness Finding 3 —\nverified VALID against `release.yml`, `test.yml:455-477`, `hatch_build.py`,\n`pyproject.toml`, `tests/unit/test_attestation_signing.py`.)\n\n## Why\n\nThe release artifact and the CI-tested code are products of different build paths.\nThe `build` job runs `python -m build` + `twine check` (a static metadata check)\nand uploads `dist/` with **no install or functional test** before `publish`\n(`release.yml` build→publish). The clean-install CI job installs the source tree\nwith `pip install .` (`test.yml:470`) — which builds a wheel in place with `.git`\npresent — so it never exercises the sdist→wheel path. The only smoke test of the\nreal artifact is documented as **post-publication** (`docs/releasing.md`), by which\npoint PyPI immutability means recovery is yank + republish.\n\nThe provenance hook computes the commit via `git rev-parse` (`None` outside a git\ntree) and `initialize` writes `_build_info.py` **unconditionally**\n(`hatch_build.py`), with no preservation of an existing baked value and no failure\nwhen the commit is absent. `python -m build`'s default builds an sdist first, then\nbuilds the wheel **from the extracted sdist** — which has no `.git` — so the\npublished **wheel** carries `COMMIT = None` while only the sdist keeps the real SHA.\nThe one test that asserts a non-null baked SHA builds a `WheelBuilder` directly\nagainst the checkout (`tests/unit/test_attestation_signing.py:202-227`), bypassing\nthe failing path, so the defect is uncaught by every existing gate.\n\n## What\n\nAdopt the pydantic / pip build-once pattern (build once → upload one artifact →\ndownload it in a separate test job that installs with the index disabled and\nexercises the public surface → download the same artifact in the publish job and\nverify hashes before publishing, never rebuilding):\n\n- **Build once**: produce wheel + sdist in one job, record SHA-256 for each, upload\n  one named artifact bundle.\n- **Test the exact wheel**: in a fresh job with no repo checkout on `PYTHONPATH`,\n  install the wheel by filename and run concrete probes — `python -c \"import rebar\"`,\n  `rebar --help`, `rebar-mcp --help`, load each packaged JSON schema, and\n  `python -c \"from rebar import _build_info; assert _build_info.COMMIT\"` — asserting\n  the embedded build info is present and non-null.\n- **Test the exact sdist**: install/build from the downloaded sdist in a clean dir,\n  run the same probes, and assert the installed package reports the intended SHA.\n- **Publish the same bytes**: `publish` `needs:` both test jobs, downloads the\n  original bundle, recomputes and compares hashes against the recorded build hashes,\n  and publishes without rebuilding.\n- **Fix the hook (decision: inject the SHA via an env var).** The workflow sets\n  `REBAR_BUILD_COMMIT=${{ github.sha }}` before `python -m build`; `hatch_build.py`'s\n  `initialize` reads `os.environ.get(\"REBAR_BUILD_COMMIT\")` as the **primary** source\n  and falls back to git when unset. This is chosen over the \"preserve existing\n  `_build_info.py`\" branch because it is simpler and auditable and does not depend on\n  the hook learning to not-overwrite.\n- **Canonical commit format = SHORT SHA (existing convention).** `signing.py` is\n  built around short SHAs throughout (`_gate_commit_sha` → `git rev-parse --short`;\n  `gate_code_version` / `rebar_version_step` docstrings say `<short-sha>[-dirty]`), so\n  to avoid a full-vs-short skew between the baked value and the live-git value in the\n  same `rebar-version:` manifest line, the new code conforms to short SHAs rather than\n  changing `signing.py`. The workflow sets `REBAR_BUILD_COMMIT` to the **short** SHA\n  (`${GITHUB_SHA::7}`, matching git's default abbreviation); the git fallback stays\n  `git rev-parse --short HEAD`; `signing.py` is unchanged. The existing provenance\n  test's `[0-9a-f]{4,}` regex still matches.\n- **Fail-fast scoped to the release context:** the hook raises (fails the build) only\n  when `REBAR_BUILD_COMMIT` is set but empty/unresolvable — so a developer's plain\n  `pip install .` (env var unset) still degrades gracefully to the git value and\n  never breaks.\n- **Verify env-var propagation (do not assume).** The fix depends on `REBAR_BUILD_COMMIT`\n  surviving from the workflow shell through `python -m build` into the Hatchling\n  `initialize` hook when the wheel is built from the extracted sdist. On the release\n  path this is guaranteed because Finding 4 builds with `--no-isolation` (no PEP 517\n  subprocess isolation at all); the plan must still **prove** it with a test that runs\n  `REBAR_BUILD_COMMIT=<short-hex> python -m build` and asserts the resulting **wheel**\n  (built from the extracted sdist) carries that exact short SHA — rather than\n  asserting propagation as settled fact.\n\n## Scope\n\n- `.github/workflows/release.yml` — build-once + two artifact-test jobs + hash-gated\n  publish (coordinate with Findings 1 and 4, which also edit this file).\n- `.github/workflows/test.yml` — optionally add a wheel/sdist artifact probe to\n  regular CI so the defect is caught pre-release, not only in the release run.\n- `hatch_build.py` — read `REBAR_BUILD_COMMIT` env var first (a short SHA), fall back\n  to `git rev-parse --short HEAD`; fail only when the env var is set but\n  empty/unresolvable (release-context fail-fast; unset = graceful git fallback for\n  dev installs).\n- `src/rebar/signing.py` — **in scope to confirm only** (no change expected): its\n  short-SHA `_gate_commit_sha` path already matches the chosen canonical short format,\n  so the baked value and the live-git value stay consistent in `gate_code_version()`\n  output regardless of install type.\n- `pyproject.toml` — adjust force-include / build config if needed for the SHA input.\n- `tests/unit/test_attestation_signing.py` — add coverage for the wheel-from-sdist\n  path (the currently-untested `COMMIT = None` case).\n- `docs/releasing.md` — **section ownership:** this story owns the \"Build-once\"\n  section only (Finding 1 owns \"Release-source authorization\", Finding 4 owns\n  \"Pinning\"), avoiding overlap across the three concurrent release stories.\n- Out of scope: byte-for-byte reproducible builds (timestamps/backend determinism)\n  beyond the SHA-256 identity check through the pipeline.\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] The release builds artifacts once and uploads a single named bundle containing\n  the wheel, the sdist, and a `SHA256SUMS` file recording their digests; `publish`\n  downloads that same bundle and runs `sha256sum -c SHA256SUMS` (failing on any\n  mismatch) before publishing — no rebuild occurs in `publish`.\n- [ ] A wheel-test job installs the exact wheel by filename with no source checkout\n  on the path and runs concrete probes — `python -c \"import rebar\"`, `rebar --help`,\n  `rebar-mcp --help`, load each packaged JSON schema, and a non-null-`COMMIT` assert;\n  an sdist-test job does the same from the sdist.\n- [ ] The shipped wheel carries a non-null **short** source commit matching the\n  release SHA — the workflow sets `REBAR_BUILD_COMMIT=${GITHUB_SHA::7}` before\n  `python -m build`, and a test (added to `tests/unit/test_attestation_signing.py`,\n  which currently only covers the direct-`WheelBuilder` path) asserts the wheel built\n  via the default sdist→wheel path contains `COMMIT` equal to that short SHA (today\n  this path yields `COMMIT = None`). The baked value and `signing.py`'s live-git\n  value share the short format, so `gate_code_version()` is consistent across install\n  types. The hook fails the build only when `REBAR_BUILD_COMMIT` is set but\n  unresolvable (release context); an unset env var falls back to git (dev\n  `pip install .` unaffected).\n- [ ] `docs/releasing.md` describes the build-once → test → publish-same-bytes flow.\n- [ ] `make lint && make typecheck && make test` pass, and the change lands via the\n  Gerrit two-vote gate."}},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"EDIT","timestamp":1784055908309825001,"uuid":"5441576e-8d04-4c33-81db-e678fac6eb7a"}